{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L9eJnj17U4CpY9H23Z99NU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough information to compile a comprehensive findings report. Let me summarize what I found:\n\n**Cluster Health:**\n- 3-node RabbitMQ cluster: rabbitmq-0, rabbitmq-1, rabbitmq-2\n- All nodes running, no alarms, no network partitions\n- Version: RabbitMQ 3.12.14 on Erlang 25.3.2.15 — **OUT OF SUPPORT** series\n- Cluster partition handling: `pause_minority` (good)\n\n**Virtual Hosts:**\n- `/` (default) — no tracing\n- `/app` — no tracing\n\n**Users:**\n- `admin` — administrator tag\n- `app-user` — no tags (no management roles)\n\n**Permissions:**\n- Default `/`: admin has full permissions; app-user has NO permissions here\n- `/app`: both admin and app-user have full permissions\n\n**Policies:**\n- None configured on either vhost\n\n**Queues and Exchanges:**\n- `/app` has `app-queue` (classic, durable queue) with only the default AMQP exchanges available\n- Default binding routes from the default exchange to `app-queue` using the routing key `app-queue`\n\n**TLS and Security:**\n- No TLS configured — only plain AMQP on port 5672 with PLAIN and AMQPLAIN auth (both unencrypted)\n- `loopback_users.guest = false` allows guest connections from anywhere, though the current user list shows only `admin` and `app-user`\n- The environment shows `{default_user,<<\"guest\">>}` indicating guest is the default user, but it's not appearing in the users list — either it was deleted or there's a mismatch between the config and actual users\n- The `loopback_users` list is empty, meaning no users are restricted to localhost-only connections\n- The config setting `loopback_users.guest = false` is a security misconfiguration since it would allow guest to connect from anywhere if it existed, though it's harmless since the user appears to be deleted\n\nNow I'm identifying the critical security issues: the AMQP and management API are running on unencrypted ports with no TLS protection.\n\nThe authentication mechanisms PLAIN and AMQPLAIN transmit credentials in plaintext, which is especially dangerous without TLS encryption.\n\nThe app-user has overly permissive permissions including configure access on the /app vhost, when application users should typically only need write and read capabilities.\n\nThe cluster lacks high-availability policies and resource protection measures like message TTL or queue length limits despite being a three-node setup.\n\nRabbitMQ 3.12.14 is no longer supported and should be upgraded to a maintained version.\n\nThe management API is exposed on all interfaces at port 15672 and should be restricted to specific networks.\n\nThere are no policies configured at all—no dead-letter exchanges, TTL settings, federation, or HA policies—which leaves the system vulnerable to resource exhaustion.\n\nThe cluster partition handling is set to pause_minority, which is actually a safe configuration, and queue distribution uses the standard min-masters locator.\n\nThere are no connection or channel limits per user, and no vhost-level limits on connections or queue counts, which could allow resource exhaustion attacks.\n\nI should also note that the kernel setting `prevent_overlapping_partitions=false` controls Erlang's network partition behavior.\n\nNow I'm writing up the findings document.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1052,"cache_read_input_tokens":40117,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1052},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01ea570c-9905-47e1-a3a5-0fdf9ab96794","uuid":"dff3b028-9ef9-41cd-bfdc-e8399066d292","request_id":"req_011CcLBzuLFHiPLnyhdjVzJn"}
