{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L9eJnj17U4CpY9H23Z99NU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PvVXdQuLJ8ct7nhbaNQhGE","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/findings.txt","content":"========================================================================\nRABBITMQ CLUSTER COMPLIANCE AUDIT — READ-ONLY\nNamespace : karma-rabbitmq-readonly-audit-20260623-122524\nAudit Date: 2026-06-23\nAuditor   : KARMA automated read-only audit agent\n========================================================================\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n1. CLUSTER HEALTH\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nCluster Name   : rabbit@rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.karma-rabbitmq-readonly-audit-20260623-122524.svc.cluster.local\nRabbitMQ Ver.  : 3.12.14  [!] OUT-OF-SUPPORT release series\nErlang Version : 25.3.2.15\nNode Count     : 3 (all disk nodes)\nAlarms         : NONE\nNetwork Partitions : NONE\nMaintenance Mode   : NONE\n\nNodes (all Running):\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  rabbit@rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n\nActive connections  : 0\nActive queues       : 1 (across all vhosts)\nVirtual host count  : 2\n\nMemory (node rabbitmq-0):\n  Total used           : ~153 MB\n  High watermark       : 40% of available (~5.4 GB)\n  Free disk watermark  : 50 MB  (current free: ~892 GB — OK)\n\nFINDING [C-01] SEVERITY: MEDIUM\n  RabbitMQ 3.12.x is explicitly marked \"out of support\" by the upstream\n  project. No security patches will be issued for this release series.\n  Recommend upgrade to a supported release (3.13.x or 4.x).\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n2. LISTENERS / NETWORK\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nPort 5672  (AMQP 0-9-1 / AMQP 1.0)  — plaintext TCP, all interfaces [::]\nPort 15672 (HTTP Management API)     — plaintext HTTP, all interfaces [::]\nPort 25672 (inter-node clustering)   — all interfaces [::]\n\nTLS Listeners : NONE (ssl_listeners = [])\nTLS Options   : NONE (ssl_options = [])\n\nFINDING [C-02] SEVERITY: HIGH\n  No TLS is configured. AMQP client traffic on port 5672 and management\n  API traffic on port 15672 are transmitted in plaintext. Credentials and\n  message payloads are exposed to network interception.\n  Recommend: configure ssl_listeners, provide CA/cert/key, disable\n  plain port 5672 for production workloads.\n\nFINDING [C-03] SEVERITY: HIGH\n  Authentication mechanisms in use: PLAIN and AMQPLAIN.\n  Both mechanisms transmit credentials in cleartext at the protocol\n  level. Without TLS, credentials are trivially intercepted.\n  Recommend: restrict to EXTERNAL (certificate-based) or ensure TLS is\n  enforced before these mechanisms are accepted.\n\nFINDING [C-04] SEVERITY: MEDIUM\n  The management API (port 15672) listens on all interfaces ([::]).\n  It should be bound to a loopback or internal-only interface, or access\n  should be restricted via a network policy, to reduce the attack surface.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n3. VIRTUAL HOSTS\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nName  Tracing\n/     false\n/app  false\n\nObservations:\n  - The default vhost \"/\" is present alongside the application vhost \"/app\".\n    If no application traffic is expected on \"/\", consider removing it to\n    reduce attack surface.\n  - Tracing is disabled on both vhosts (correct for production).\n\nFINDING [C-05] SEVERITY: LOW\n  Default vhost \"/\" is retained. Unless it serves a purpose, it should be\n  removed to enforce strict vhost separation and least-privilege access.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n4. USERS AND AUTHENTICATION\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nUser      Tags\nadmin     [administrator]\napp-user  [] (no management role)\n\nNo guest user exists (deleted or never created — OK).\n\nGlobal parameter loopback_users = [] (from environment):\n  No user is restricted to loopback-only access.\n\nConfiguration file sets:  loopback_users.guest = false\n  This is only relevant if a guest user is created in the future; as-is\n  it has no effect since the guest user does not exist.\n\nFINDING [C-06] SEVERITY: LOW\n  The configuration file contains `loopback_users.guest = false`, which\n  would allow a future `guest` account (default password \"guest\") to\n  connect from any network host. If the guest user is ever recreated\n  accidentally (e.g. by a reset), it will be globally accessible.\n  Recommend setting `loopback_users.guest = true` as a defence-in-depth\n  measure.\n\nFINDING [C-07] SEVERITY: INFORMATIONAL\n  No user-level connection or channel limits are set for either user.\n  Consider adding limits to prevent resource exhaustion from runaway clients.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n5. PERMISSIONS\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nVhost \"/\"\n  User    Configure  Write  Read\n  admin   .*         .*     .*\n\nVhost \"/app\"\n  User      Configure  Write  Read\n  admin     .*         .*     .*\n  app-user  .*         .*     .*\n\nFINDING [C-08] SEVERITY: MEDIUM\n  app-user has full \"configure\" permission (pattern: .*) on the /app vhost.\n  The \"configure\" permission allows the user to create and delete exchanges,\n  queues, and bindings. For an application service account this is\n  overly broad; typical app users only need write + read permissions.\n  Recommend restricting app-user configure permission to \"\" (empty) or a\n  narrow pattern matching only the queues/exchanges it must manage.\n\nFINDING [C-09] SEVERITY: LOW\n  admin has full permissions on both \"/\" and \"/app\". Ensure admin credentials\n  are not embedded in application code or stored insecurely. No secondary\n  admin or monitoring-only user is configured for audit purposes.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n6. POLICIES\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nVhost \"/\"  : no policies defined\nVhost \"/app\": no policies defined\n\nFINDING [C-10] SEVERITY: MEDIUM\n  No high-availability or quorum-queue policies are defined, despite the\n  cluster running 3 nodes. The single queue \"app-queue\" is a CLASSIC queue\n  with no mirroring configuration. If node rabbitmq-0 fails, that queue's\n  data may be unavailable or lost.\n  Recommend: define a policy to promote app-queue to a quorum queue\n  (x-queue-type: quorum) for durability and leader election across nodes.\n\nFINDING [C-11] SEVERITY: LOW\n  No message TTL (message-ttl) or queue length limit (max-length) policies\n  are configured. Unbounded queues can exhaust memory/disk under backpressure.\n  Recommend: add a policy with `message-ttl` and `max-length-bytes` for\n  resource protection.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n7. QUEUES\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nVhost /app:\n  Name       Type     Durable  Auto-delete  Arguments\n  app-queue  classic  true     false        (none)\n\nVhost /:\n  (no queues)\n\nBindings (vhost /app):\n  default exchange → app-queue  (routing key: app-queue)\n\nFINDING [C-12] SEVERITY: MEDIUM\n  \"app-queue\" uses the classic queue type. Classic queues store data on a\n  single node and rely on optional mirroring policies for HA. With no HA\n  policy set (see C-10), this queue has no redundancy.\n  Recommend: migrate to a quorum queue for built-in replication across the\n  3-node cluster.\n\nFINDING [C-13] SEVERITY: INFORMATIONAL\n  Only default AMQP exchanges are present in /app. No dead-letter exchange\n  (DLX) is configured for app-queue. Undeliverable or expired messages will\n  be silently dropped. Consider adding a DLX for observability.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n8. TLS / CERTIFICATE CONFIGURATION\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nssl_listeners   : [] (none)\nssl_options     : [] (none)\nSSL protocol    : ['tlsv1.3', 'tlsv1.2'] (configured but unused)\nClient cert auth: ssl_cert_login_from = distinguished_name (configured but\n                  not active since no TLS listener is running)\n\nFINDING [C-14] SEVERITY: HIGH  (see also C-02, C-03)\n  TLS is not deployed. The configuration contains TLS protocol version\n  settings (TLS 1.2/1.3) and ssl_cert_login_from, indicating TLS was\n  intended but not completed. The absence of ssl_listeners means these\n  settings have no effect.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n9. ENABLED PLUGINS\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nPlugins (from ConfigMap rabbitmq-config):\n  rabbitmq_management\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s\n\nActive at runtime (per rabbitmqctl status):\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s\n  rabbitmq_peer_discovery_common\n  rabbitmq_management\n  rabbitmq_management_agent\n  rabbitmq_web_dispatch\n  amqp_client\n  cowboy\n  cowlib\n\nObservations:\n  - No shovel, federation, or LDAP plugin is enabled.\n  - rabbitmq_management exposes the HTTP API and UI; see finding C-04.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n10. CONFIGURATION FILE SUMMARY\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSource: ConfigMap \"rabbitmq-config\" → /etc/rabbitmq/rabbitmq.conf\n\n  cluster_formation.peer_discovery_backend = rabbit_peer_discovery_k8s\n  cluster_formation.k8s.host               = kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local\n  cluster_formation.k8s.service_name       = rabbitmq-headless\n  cluster_formation.k8s.address_type       = hostname\n  cluster_formation.k8s.hostname_suffix    = .<ns>.svc.cluster.local\n  cluster_partition_handling               = pause_minority   [GOOD]\n  queue_master_locator                     = min-masters      [OK]\n  loopback_users.guest                     = false            [see C-06]\n  listeners.tcp.default                    = 5672\n  management.tcp.port                      = 15672\n\n  cluster_partition_handling = pause_minority is a safe choice: the minority\n  side pauses (rather than forming a split-brain cluster) during a network\n  partition. This is a correct production setting.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n11. FEATURE FLAGS\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nAll cluster feature flags are in the \"enabled\" state, including:\n  quorum_queue, stream_queue, classic_mirrored_queue_version,\n  user_limits, virtual_host_metadata, maintenance_mode_status (all enabled).\n\nThis is consistent with a fully-initialized 3.12.x cluster where all nodes\njoined at the same version.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n12. VHOST AND USER LIMITS\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nVhost \"/\" limits  : none set\nVhost \"/app\" limits: none set\nUser \"admin\" limits : none set\nUser \"app-user\" limits: none set\n\nSee finding C-07 and C-11 for recommendations.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nFINDINGS SUMMARY\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nID    Severity       Title\n----  -------------  ---------------------------------------------------\nC-02  HIGH           No TLS — AMQP and management API are plaintext\nC-03  HIGH           PLAIN/AMQPLAIN auth without TLS exposes credentials\nC-14  HIGH           TLS configured but not deployed (incomplete setup)\nC-01  MEDIUM         RabbitMQ 3.12.x is out of support\nC-04  MEDIUM         Management API bound to all interfaces\nC-08  MEDIUM         app-user has overly broad configure permission\nC-10  MEDIUM         No HA/quorum policy on 3-node cluster\nC-11  MEDIUM         No TTL or queue-length policies (unbounded queues)\nC-12  MEDIUM         app-queue is classic type with no replication\nC-05  LOW            Default vhost \"/\" retained unnecessarily\nC-06  LOW            loopback_users.guest=false risks future guest exposure\nC-09  LOW            No read-only monitoring user; single admin account\nC-07  INFO           No per-user connection/channel limits\nC-13  INFO           No dead-letter exchange for app-queue\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nEND OF AUDIT REPORT\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1052,"cache_read_input_tokens":40117,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1052},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"01ea570c-9905-47e1-a3a5-0fdf9ab96794","uuid":"7dadb20d-4b23-4e00-92f4-2176f40912f6","request_id":"req_011CcLBzuLFHiPLnyhdjVzJn"}
